<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Frost Blanket for Tomatoes</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    The best frost blanket for tomatoes is the one that protects against real cold without being so heavy or awkward that it never gets used properly.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most home gardeners, the best frost blanket for tomatoes is a medium-weight, breathable cover that provides protection from light frost while remaining easy to handle and secure.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Tomatoes are highly sensitive to cold. Even light frost can damage or kill plants quickly, especially early or late in the season.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good frost blanket can help protect plants from marginal cold, buy time during unexpected weather swings, and extend the season slightly when conditions are close to the edge.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Kind of Frost Blanket Is Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best for most gardeners:</strong> medium-weight frost cloth that balances protection and ease of use.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for light frost only:</strong> lighter blanket that is easy to apply quickly.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for repeated cold nights:</strong> slightly heavier fabric with better insulating ability.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The key is matching the blanket to the level of cold you are actually trying to protect against.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What a Frost Blanket for Tomatoes Actually Needs to Do</h2>

  <p>
    A frost blanket should trap a small amount of heat around the plant and reduce exposure to cold air and frost formation.
  </p>

  <p>
    It should also be breathable enough to avoid overheating during the day and flexible enough to apply quickly when weather changes.
  </p>

  <p>
    The best blanket is one that fits into your routine and can be used reliably when needed.
  </p>
</section>

