<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Fabric Weight Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Frost blankets come in different weights, which affect how much insulation they provide.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Lighter blankets:</strong> easier to use but offer less protection.</li>
    <li><strong>Heavier blankets:</strong> provide more protection but can be harder to manage.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For tomatoes, a middle-ground option is usually best because it protects against common conditions without becoming difficult to handle.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Direct Cover vs Supported Cover</h2>

  <p>
    Frost blankets can be placed directly over tomato plants, but support often improves performance.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Direct cover:</strong> simple and fast, but may press on plants.</li>
    <li><strong>Supported cover:</strong> creates air space and improves protection.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For larger plants or repeated use, supported setups usually work better.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/best-row-cover-hoops-for-raised-beds/">best row cover hoops for raised beds</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in a Frost Blanket</h2>

  <h3>1. Appropriate Temperature Protection</h3>
  <p>
    The blanket should match the level of cold you expect. Overbuying for extreme conditions is less useful than matching typical frost risk.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Breathability</h3>
  <p>
    Breathable fabric helps prevent overheating during the day and allows moisture to escape.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Ease of Use</h3>
  <p>
    A blanket should be easy to deploy quickly, especially when frost is unexpected.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Size and Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    The blanket should cover the plant fully, reaching the ground to trap warmth effectively.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Durability</h3>
  <p>
    If you plan to reuse it, durability matters. Thin materials may not last through repeated use.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Frost Blankets Actually Work</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Light frost conditions</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Short cold periods overnight</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Marginal temperature dips near freezing</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In these situations, frost blankets can make a meaningful difference.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Frost Blankets Are Not Enough</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Hard freezes</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Extended cold periods</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Very low overnight temperatures</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Frost blankets are designed to buffer conditions, not to fully protect against severe cold.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Overlook</h2>

  <p>
    One of the biggest factors in effectiveness is how well the blanket is secured.
  </p>

  <p>
    Gaps at the bottom allow heat to escape and cold air to enter. A properly secured blanket often performs much better than a loosely applied one.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/best-clips-and-hoops-for-securing-frost-cloth/">best clips and hoops for securing frost cloth</a>.
  </p>
</section>

