<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Frost Blankets</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Choosing blankets that are too light:</strong> insufficient protection.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing blankets that are too heavy:</strong> harder to use regularly.</li>
    <li><strong>Not covering plants fully:</strong> reduces effectiveness.</li>
    <li><strong>Using blankets too late:</strong> after frost damage has already occurred.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best results come from matching the blanket to the situation and using it proactively.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Buy</h2>

  <p>
    For most tomato growers, buy a medium-weight frost blanket that is breathable, easy to handle, and large enough to cover your plants fully. Pair it with simple supports if you plan to use it repeatedly.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choose lighter blankets for quick, occasional use and slightly heavier ones if your season regularly includes multiple cold nights. Focus on ease of use and consistent application rather than maximum insulation.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best frost blanket is the one you can deploy quickly and use consistently when it matters.
  </p>
